{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526813"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:26:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:26:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14158"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14158"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.17,0.02,0.2,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6841"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101915"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6841"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14158"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84371"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4020"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35427"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101915"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man is admitted to hospital with community-acquired pneumonia. He does not speak English and communication is difficult despite attempts to use an interpreter service. Two days after admission, he becomes increasingly agitated and distressed. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on 2 L/min oxygen, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He is diaphoretic with dilated pupils. He has rhinorrhoea, lacrimation, and is repeatedly rubbing his legs complaining of muscle aches through gestures. His chest examination reveals right lower zone crackles. He is restless, yawning frequently, and keeps trying to leave his bed. His medical records show no history of mental health conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Opioid withdrawal","Delirium tremens","Acute psychosis","Alcohol withdrawal","Septic encephalopathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eopioid withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s presentation includes a constellation of symptoms highly characteristic of opioid withdrawal: agitation, diaphoresis (sweating), tachycardia, dilated pupils, rhinorrhoea (runny nose), lacrimation (watery eyes), muscle aches, restlessness, and yawning. This collection of symptoms is often referred to as a \u0022flu-like syndrome\u0022 but with prominent autonomic and psychological features. Opioid withdrawal typically begins within 6-12 hours after the last opioid use for short-acting opioids and peaks within 72 hours, which aligns with the timeline of this patient\u0027s hospital admission. It is likely that this patient was using opioids regularly prior to admission, and this use was interrupted during hospitalisation, precipitating withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelirium tremens\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe form of alcohol withdrawal that typically occurs 48-96 hours after the last drink. While it can present with agitation and autonomic instability (tachycardia, hypertension, fever), it usually includes more severe symptoms such as visual hallucinations, tactile hallucinations (formication), severe confusion, and seizures. The characteristic coarse tremor of alcohol withdrawal is not described in this case, and the dilated pupils, rhinorrhoea, and muscle aches are more consistent with opioid withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute psychosis\u003C/strong\u003E could present with agitation and unusual behaviour, but would not typically cause the physical signs of sweating, tachycardia, dilated pupils, rhinorrhoea, and muscle aches seen in this patient. Additionally, there is no mention of hallucinations, delusions, or thought disorder that would be expected in acute psychosis. The absence of a prior psychiatric history also makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly to opioid withdrawal, with agitation, sweating, and tachycardia. However, alcohol withdrawal typically includes tremors as a prominent feature, which are not mentioned in this case. Additionally, pupillary dilation is more characteristic of opioid withdrawal than alcohol withdrawal, which often presents with normal pupils. The rhinorrhoea, lacrimation, and muscle aches described are also more consistent with opioid withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility given the patient\u0027s admission for pneumonia. However, septic encephalopathy typically presents with a more fluctuating level of consciousness, often progressing to lethargy or coma, rather than the agitation and restlessness described here. The specific constellation of symptoms (dilated pupils, rhinorrhoea, muscle aches) would be unusual for septic encephalopathy and points more strongly toward opioid withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of opioid withdrawal typically involves opioid replacement therapy with methadone or buprenorphine, symptomatic treatment with clonidine for autonomic symptoms, and supportive care. It is important to note that the language barrier in this case complicates the assessment, highlighting the importance of recognising physical signs and symptoms, especially in patients with communication difficulties. Obtaining a detailed substance use history through an interpreter would be an important next step.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Opioid withdrawal presents with a characteristic constellation of symptoms including agitation, diaphoresis, tachycardia, dilated pupils, rhinorrhoea, and muscle aches.","Patients admitted for other conditions may experience opioid withdrawal if their regular opioid use is interrupted during hospitalisation.","Language barriers can significantly complicate the assessment of patients experiencing withdrawal syndromes, highlighting the importance of recognising physical signs."],"references":["Srivastava AB, Mariani JJ\u003C Levin FR. New directions in the treatment of opioid withdrawal. Lancet 2020; 395:1938-48."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84371"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14158"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84371"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-05T08:27:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-05T08:42:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6841"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101915"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i